  "title": "Liver surface anatomy",
  "body_html": "<b>Surface anatomy</b><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti227b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti227.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating approximate position of liver. Note the liver moves with respiration</div><br /><b>Superior surface</b> <br /><ul><li>Reaches the 5th rib on the right</li><li>Reaches 6th rib 7cm from midline on the left</li></ul><b>Inferior border</b><br /><ul><li>Just below the 10th rib on the right side</li><li>Inferior border can be marked by line from 10th costal cartilage right midaxillary line to 6th rib left midclavicular line. </li></ul><b>Lateral view</b><br /><ul><li>Laterally the superior border of the liver reaches the 6th rib in the mid-axillary line</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti216b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti216.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view of the liver</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti217b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti217.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Posterior view of the liver. Note the stomach obscures the left lobe of the liver in this image. The stomach has been removed on the illustrations below</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdomen'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>The 9 region abdominal anatomical scheme uses the vertical midclavicular lines and horizontal transpyloric and transtubercular planes to divide the abdomen into 9 regions</div><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb128b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb128.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/liver'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb128b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior and posterior views of the liver</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb129b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb129.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/liver'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb129b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>The green lines highlight Cantlie's line, a vertical line drawn between the IVC superiorly and gallbladder fossa. Cantile's line separates the functional lobes where as the falciform ligament separates the anatomical lobes </div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Anatomy</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Abdomen & pelvis anatomy</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<b>Surface anatomy</b><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti227b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti227.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Diagram illustrating approximate position of liver. Note the liver moves with respiration</div><br /><b>Superior surface</b> <br /><ul><li>Reaches the 5th rib on the right</li><li>Reaches 6th rib 7cm from midline on the left</li></ul><b>Inferior border</b><br /><ul><li>Just below the 10th rib on the right side</li><li>Inferior border can be marked by line from 10th costal cartilage right midaxillary line to 6th rib left midclavicular line. </li></ul><b>Lateral view</b><br /><ul><li>Laterally the superior border of the liver reaches the 6th rib in the mid-axillary line</li></ul><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti216b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti216.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Anterior view of the liver</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti217b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti217.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Posterior view of the liver. Note the stomach obscures the left lobe of the liver in this image. The stomach has been removed on the illustrations below</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdomen'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb348b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>The 9 region abdominal 